Paul:

I downloaded and installed Thoth.  I think the shapes of the letters 
look very good at first sight.  There are a couple of weird things 
happening though, and I&#39;m not sure what is causing it.  When I type 
&quot;I-t&quot; and then space, the letter is changing to &quot;E-at.&quot;  Also, when I 
typed the word &quot;don&#39;t&quot; and then space, the vowel changes to &quot;O-n.&quot; and 
an apostrophe appears between the n and t.  Does this make any sense?

In any event, congratulations on a fine new addition to QS fonts.

Paige

Paul Tremblay wrote:
&gt;
&gt; I have released a new font, which you can find in the files section in
&gt; the fonts directory. The new font is called Thoth. It also has a
&gt; counterpart, ThothUni, the Unicode version.
&gt;
&gt; The Unicode version is based on the popular Gentium font, so it contains
&gt; thousands of glyphs, and one can use just ThothUni to mix up Traditional
&gt; orthography and QS in the same document by using just one font.
&gt;
&gt; I consider Thoth to still be in its testing stage, so I appreciate any
&gt; feedback. In the zip file you will find the two fonts and a number of
&gt; PDF documents that I created using this font. The font looks best with a
&gt; program that recognizes the kerning (special space between letters). I
&gt; found that only XeLaTeX and InDesign recognized kerning. For this
&gt; reason, I included the PDF produced with XeLaTeX so you can see what the
&gt; font looks like displayed properly.
&gt;
&gt; Paul
&gt;
&gt;  


